                    <i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i>
                    <h3>What is Ecological Site Inspection?</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Ecological site inspection is a systematic process of assessing and documenting the ecological values, conditions, and potential impacts of a specific area. In Tasmania, these inspections are crucial for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Conservation planning and management</li>
                    <li>Development assessment and approval processes</li>
                    <li>Monitoring ecosystem health and changes over time</li>
                    <li>Identifying threatened species and communities</li>
                    <li>Informing restoration and rehabilitation efforts</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-clipboard-list"></i>
                    <h3>Inspection Process Overview</h3>
                </div>
                <p>A comprehensive ecological site inspection typically involves these key steps:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Pre-inspection planning</strong> - Review existing information, maps, and data</li>
                    <li><strong>Site assessment</strong> - Field inspection documenting flora, fauna, and ecological communities</li>
                    <li><strong>Threat identification</strong> - Recording weeds, pests, erosion, and other impacts</li>
                    <li><strong>Data recording</strong> - Systematic documentation using standard forms and methods</li>
                    <li><strong>Analysis and reporting</strong> - Evaluating significance and preparing recommendations</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
                    <h3>Why Tasmania is Special</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Tasmania's unique ecological characteristics require specialized inspection approaches:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>World Heritage Areas with exceptional universal value</li>
                    <li>High number of endemic species found nowhere else on Earth</li>
                    <li>Diverse ecosystems ranging from alpine to coastal environments</li>
                    <li>Significant Aboriginal cultural heritage values intertwined with ecological values</li>
                    <li>Specific legislative requirements under Tasmanian law</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Key Concepts Section -->
        <section id="concepts" class="content-section">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Key Concepts in Ecological Site Inspection</h2>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i> TasVeg Vegetation Classification</h4>
                <p>TasVeg is Tasmania's official vegetation classification system that describes and maps native vegetation communities across the state. Understanding TasVeg is essential for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identifying the conservation significance of vegetation communities</li>
                    <li>Assessing vegetation quality and condition against benchmark descriptions</li>
                    <li>Setting appropriate management objectives for different vegetation types</li>
                    <li>Determining offset requirements for development applications</li>
                    <li>Prioritizing conservation efforts based on vegetation rarity and threat status</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-search"></i> Rapid Habitat Assessment</h4>
                <p>Rapid habitat assessment techniques allow for efficient evaluation of ecological values during site inspections. Key components include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Vegetation structure and composition assessment</li>
                    <li>Habitat features evaluation (logs, rocks, hollows)</li>
                    <li>Weed and disturbance mapping</li>
                    <li>Condition scoring using standardized metrics</li>
                    <li>Comparison with TasVeg benchmark descriptions</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i> Legislation and Policy Framework</h4>
                <p>Ecological site inspections in Tasmania must consider multiple legislative instruments:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999</strong> (Commonwealth)</li>
                    <li><strong>Nature Conservation Act 2002</strong> (Tasmania)</li>
                    <li><strong>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995</strong> (Tasmania)</li>
                    <li><strong>Vegetation Management Bill 2023</strong> (proposed Tasmanian legislation)</li>
                    <li>Various local government planning schemes</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-camera"></i> Documentation Methods</h4>
                <p>Proper documentation is essential for ecological site inspections:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Standardized data collection forms aligned with TasVeg methodology</li>
                    <li>Geotagged photography with scale references</li>
                    <li>GPS mapping of boundaries and features</li>
                    <li>Sketch maps showing key features and transects</li>
