                <div class="tas-example">
                    <h4>Rainforest & Related Scrub (TASVEG codes prefixed “R”, e.g. RMT, RFS, RSH, RKF, etc.)</h4>
                    <p>Tasmania’s cool temperate rainforests are ancient, moist forests found in high-rainfall and sheltered areas, mainly in the state’s west and south-west. They are typically dominated by myrtle beech (Nothofagus cunninghamii), with sassafras (Atherosperma moschatum), leatherwood (Eucryphia lucida), and a variety of ferns and mosses in the understorey. These forests provide critical habitat for many endemic and moisture-loving species and play an important role in carbon storage. In TASVEG, they are included in the Rainforest and Related Scrub group (codes beginning with “R”).</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tas-example">
                    <h4>Highland / Alpine Vegetation (TASVEG codes prefixed “H”) </h4>
                    <p>At higher elevations (typically above 800–1,000 m, depending on exposure), Tasmania supports distinctive vegetation communities adapted to cold, wet, and windy conditions. These include cushion plants that form dense mats close to the ground, alpine heaths with low woody shrubs, and alpine moorlands and bogs dominated by sedges, rushes, and sphagnum moss. These environments are slow to recover from disturbance and are highly sensitive to changes in climate and fire. In TASVEG, they are mapped within the Highland Treeless Vegetation group (codes beginning with “H”).</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="tas-example">
                    <h4>Coastal Heathland & Sedgeland / Grassland (TASVEG codes in the “S” and “A / M” groups)</h4>
                    <p>Tasmania’s coastline supports heathland, scrub, and salt-tolerant sedgeland and grassland communities that thrive in exposed, nutrient-poor, and sandy soils. These areas provide important habitat for ground-nesting birds, pollinators, and many endemic plant species. Coastal heathland is usually mapped as SCH within the Scrub, Heathland and Coastal Complexes, while coastal sedgeland or grassland communities are represented within the Moorland, Sedgeland, Rushland and Peatland group (e.g. ASS, ARS), depending on site conditions.</p>
                </div>
