        <!-- Tasmanian Ecosystems Section -->
        <section id="ecosystems" class="content-section active" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="ecosystems-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-mountain" aria-hidden="true"></i> Unique Tasmanian Ecosystems</h2>
            <p>Tasmania's isolation and varied topography have created diverse and unique ecosystems found nowhere else on Earth.</p>
            
            <div class="learning-objectives">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-bullseye" aria-hidden="true"></i> Learning Objectives</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify the major ecosystem types found in Tasmania</li>
                    <li>Understand the key characteristics of each ecosystem</li>
                    <li>Recognize the conservation significance of Tasmanian ecosystems</li>
                    <li>Describe the Gondwanan heritage of Tasmania's flora and fauna</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="ecosystem-gallery">
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-tree" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Cool Temperate Rainforests</h3>
                        <p>Characterized by myrtle beech, sassafras, and leatherwood trees. These ancient forests have remained largely unchanged for millions of years.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-mountain" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Alpine Ecosystems</h3>
                        <p>Found above 800m elevation, featuring cushion plants, pencil pines, and unique high-altitude flora adapted to harsh conditions.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-tree" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Eucalypt Forests</h3>
                        <p>Diverse forests dominated by various eucalypt species, providing habitat for many endemic animals.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-water" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Coastal Heathlands</h3>
                        <p>Wind-swept communities of low-growing shrubs and herbs adapted to saline conditions and poor soils.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-tint" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Wetlands & Buttongrass Moorlands</h3>
                        <p>Peat-accumulating ecosystems with unique hydrological characteristics and specialized plant communities.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="ecosystem-item">
                    <div class="ecosystem-img">
                        <i class="fas fa-water" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ecosystem-content">
                        <h3>Marine Ecosystems</h3>
                        <p>Kelp forests, seagrass meadows, and sponge gardens that support diverse marine life including many endemic species.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-lightbulb" aria-hidden="true"></i> Key Concept: Gondwanan Heritage</h3>
                <p>Tasmania's ecosystems are living relics of the ancient supercontinent Gondwana. Many plant species have remained virtually unchanged for 60 million years, making these ecosystems of global significance.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-info-circle" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Key Characteristics of Tasmanian Ecosystems</h3>
                </div>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Gondwanan Heritage:</strong> Many plant species are relics from the ancient supercontinent Gondwana</li>
                    <li><strong>High Endemism:</strong> Isolation has led to the evolution of many species found nowhere else</li>
                    <li><strong>Climate Refugia:</strong> Tasmania served as a refuge for species during past climate changes</li>
                    <li><strong>Fire Adaptation:</strong> Many ecosystems have evolved with fire as a natural disturbance regime</li>
                    <li><strong>Nutrient-Poor Soils:</strong> Many plants have specialized adaptations for nutrient acquisition</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tas-example">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i> TAS Example: Tarkine Wilderness</h3>
                <p>The Tarkine region in northwest Tasmania contains the largest single tract of cool temperate rainforest in Australia, spanning over 180,000 hectares. This area represents one of the most significant Gondwanan remnants in the world and supports an incredible diversity of flora and fauna, including many threatened species.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Endemic Species Section -->
        <section id="species" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="species-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-paw" aria-hidden="true"></i> Endemic Species of Tasmania</h2>
            <p>Tasmania's isolation has resulted in numerous species that are found nowhere else in the world.</p>
            
            <div class="learning-objectives">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-bullseye" aria-hidden="true"></i> Learning Objectives</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify key endemic species of Tasmania</li>
                    <li>Understand the conservation status of threatened species</li>
                    <li>Recognize the ecological roles of different endemic species</li>
                    <li>Describe the unique adaptations of Tasmanian flora and fauna</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Iconic Endemic Mammals</h3>
            <div class="species-grid">
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-paw" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Tasmanian Devil</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">World's largest carnivorous marsupial, known for its powerful jaws and feisty temperament.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-paw" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Eastern Quoll</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">Spotted carnivorous marsupial, extinct on mainland Australia but surviving in Tasmania.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-paw" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Tasmanian Pademelon</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">Small, stocky macropod with a distinctive short tail and thick fur.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-paw" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Tasmanian Bettong</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">Small, nocturnal macropod that uses its prehensile tail to gather nesting material.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Unique Flora</h3>
            <div class="species-grid">
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-leaf" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Huon Pine</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">One of the longest-living trees in the world, with some specimens over 3,000 years old.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-leaf" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Leatherwood</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">Unique to Tasmania's rainforests, produces flowers that are the source of distinctive honey.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-leaf" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Pencil Pine</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">Coniferous tree found in high-altitude areas, extremely slow-growing and long-lived.</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="species-item">
                    <div class="species-thumb">
                        <i class="fas fa-leaf" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="species-name">Tasmanian Blue Gum</div>
                    <div class="species-desc">The floral emblem of Tasmania, one of the tallest flowering plants in the world.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-lightbulb" aria-hidden="true"></i> Key Concept: Endemism</h3>
                <p>Endemic species are those found naturally in only one geographic location. Tasmania's long isolation has created ideal conditions for endemism, with approximately 30% of Tasmania's terrestrial mammals, 15% of its birds, and 25% of its plants being endemic to the island.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Species of Conservation Significance</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Many Tasmanian species are threatened and protected under state and federal legislation:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Swift Parrot:</strong> Critically endangered migratory bird that breeds only in Tasmania</li>
                    <li><strong>Orange-bellied Parrot:</strong> One of Australia's most endangered birds with fewer than 50 left in the wild</li>
                    <li><strong>Giant Freshwater Crayfish:</strong> World's largest freshwater invertebrate, found only in northern Tasmania</li>
                    <li><strong>Tasmanian Wedge-tailed Eagle:</strong> Unique subspecies with a population of less than 1,000 breeding pairs</li>
                    <li><strong>Spotted-tail Quoll:</strong> Largest native carnivore on mainland Australia but declining in Tasmania</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tas-example">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i> TAS Example: Maria Island Sanctuary</h3>
                <p>Maria Island serves as an important insurance population site for several threatened Tasmanian species. The island is free of foxes and other key threats, making it an ideal location for reintroduction programs for species like the Tasmanian devil and eastern quoll.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="summary-box">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-clipboard-list" aria-hidden="true"></i> Summary: Endemic Species Protection</h3>
                <p>Protecting Tasmania's unique species requires:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Habitat conservation and restoration</li>
                    <li>Threat management (predators, disease, habitat loss)</li>
                    <li>Monitoring and research programs</li>
                    <li>Insurance populations and captive breeding</li>
                    <li>Community engagement and education</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Ecosystem Threats Section -->
        <section id="threats" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="threats-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle" aria-hidden="true"></i> Ecosystem Threats</h2>
            <p>Tasmania's unique ecosystems face numerous threats that require careful management and conservation efforts.</p>
            
            <div class="learning-objectives">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-bullseye" aria-hidden="true"></i> Learning Objectives</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify major threats to Tasmanian ecosystems</li>
                    <li>Understand the impacts of climate change on different ecosystems</li>
                    <li>Recognize the ecological damage caused by invasive species</li>
                    <li>Describe how habitat fragmentation affects biodiversity</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-fire" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Climate Change</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Climate change poses significant threats to Tasmania's ecosystems:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Alpine ecosystem shrinkage:</strong> Rising temperatures are reducing the area of alpine habitats</li>
                    <li><strong>Sea level rise:</strong> Threatening coastal ecosystems and species</li>
                    <li><strong>Changed fire regimes:</strong> Altered frequency and intensity of bushfires</li>
                    <li><strong>Ocean acidification:</strong> Affecting marine ecosystems and species</li>
                    <li><strong>Species range shifts:</strong> Changing distributions of plants and animals</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-seedling" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Invasive Species</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Introduced plants and animals threaten native biodiversity:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Weeds:</strong> Spanish heath, gorse, blackberry, and willow species outcompete native vegetation</li>
                    <li><strong>Feral animals:</strong> Cats, foxes, rabbits, and deer impact native species through predation and competition</li>
                    <li><strong>Pathogens:</strong> Phytophthora root rot and other diseases affect native plants</li>
                    <li><strong>Marine pests:</strong> Introduced species threaten marine ecosystems</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-lightbulb" aria-hidden="true"></i> Key Concept: Invasive Species Impacts</h3>
                <p>Invasive species are the second greatest threat to biodiversity after habitat destruction. In Tasmania, invasive species have contributed to the decline of numerous native plants and animals, altered ecosystem processes, and changed fire regimes.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-hard-hat" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Habitat Loss and Fragmentation</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Human activities continue to impact natural habitats:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Land clearing:</strong> For agriculture, urban development, and forestry</li>
                    <li><strong>Infrastructure development:</strong> Roads, powerlines, and other linear infrastructure fragment habitats</li>
                    <li><strong>Hydrological changes:</strong> Dams, drainage, and water extraction alter wetland ecosystems</li>
                    <li><strong>Coastal development:</strong> Impacting sensitive coastal and marine environments</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card header">
                    <i class="fas fa-disease" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Disease</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Disease outbreaks threaten vulnerable species:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Devil Facial Tumor Disease (DFTD):</strong> Contagious cancer that has devastated Tasmanian devil populations</li>
                    <li><strong>Chytrid fungus:</strong> Threatening amphibian populations</li>
                    <li><strong>Phytophthora cinnamomi:</strong> Root rot fungus affecting many plant species</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tas-example">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i> TAS Example: Fox Incursion</h3>
                <p>Red foxes made their way into Tasmania in the 2000s, posing a catastrophic threat to native wildlife. A comprehensive eradication program was established, involving baiting, monitoring, and community reporting. While no established population currently exists, ongoing vigilance is required to prevent establishment.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="summary-box">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-clipboard-list" aria-hidden="true"></i> Summary: Threat Management Priorities</h3>
                <p>Effective threat management requires:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Prevention of new invasions through biosecurity</li>
                    <li>Early detection and rapid response to new threats</li>
                    <li>Strategic control of established threats</li>
                    <li>Ongoing monitoring and evaluation</li>
                    <li>Community involvement and awareness</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Conservation Strategies Section -->
        <section id="strategies" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="strategies-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-seedling" aria-hidden="true"></i> Conservation Strategies</h2>
            <p>Effective conservation requires a multi-faceted approach tailored to Tasmania's unique ecosystems.</p>
            
            <div class="learning-objectives">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-bullseye" aria-hidden="true"></i> Learning Objectives</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identify key conservation strategies used in Tasmania</li>
                    <li>Understand the role of protected areas in conservation</li>
                    <li>Describe threatened species recovery programs</li>
                    <li>Recognize the importance of community engagement in conservation</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-shield-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Protected Areas</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Tasmania has an extensive network of protected areas covering approximately 40% of the state:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>National Parks:</strong> 19 national parks protect representative examples of major ecosystems</li>
                    <li><strong>World Heritage Area:</strong> The Tasmanian Wilderness World Heritage Area covers 1.58 million hectares</li>
                    <li><strong>Nature Reserves:</strong> More than 400 reserves protect specific natural values</li>
                    <li><strong>Marine Protected Areas:</strong> 14 marine reserves protect coastal and marine ecosystems</li>
                    <li><strong>Private Land Conservation:</strong> Conservation covenants and agreements on private land</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-concept">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-lightbulb" aria-hidden="true"></i> Key Concept: Conservation Planning</h3>
                <p>Systematic conservation planning involves identifying areas that comprehensively represent regional biodiversity while considering threats, costs, and opportunities. Tasmania uses this approach to guide expansion of the protected area network and prioritize conservation actions.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-sync-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Threatened Species Recovery</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Targeted programs for species of conservation concern:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Save the Tasmanian Devil Program:</strong> Insurance populations, disease research, and monitoring</li>
                    <li><strong>Orange-bellied Parrot Recovery:</strong> Captive breeding and release, habitat management</li>
                    <li><strong>Giant Freshwater Crayfish protection:</strong> Habitat protection, water quality management</li>
                    <li><strong>Swift Parrot conservation:</strong> Protection of breeding habitat and winter foraging resources</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-users" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Community Engagement</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Involving the community in conservation efforts:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Landcare and Bushcare groups:</strong> Community-based restoration projects</li>
                    <li><strong>Citizen science programs:</strong> Involving the public in monitoring and data collection</li>
                    <li><strong>Indigenous partnerships:</strong> Working with Aboriginal communities for cultural and natural resource management</li>
                    <li><strong>Education programs:</strong> Raising awareness about Tasmania's unique biodiversity</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-tools" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Threat Management</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Specific approaches to managing key threats:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Weed management:</strong> Strategic control programs for priority weed species</li>
                    <li><strong>Feral animal control:</strong> Targeted programs for cats, foxes, rabbits, and deer</li>
                    <li><strong>Fire management:</strong> Planned burning to maintain ecosystem health and reduce wildfire risk</li>
                    <li><strong>Biosecurity:</strong> Preventing the introduction and spread of new pests and diseases</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tas-example">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt" aria-hidden="true"></i> TAS Example: Land for Wildlife</h3>
                <p>The Land for Wildlife program supports private landholders to manage wildlife habitat on their properties. Participants receive technical advice, resources, and recognition for their conservation efforts. This program has been highly successful in Tasmania, with over 1,200 properties covering more than 200,000 hectares participating.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-balance-scale" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Policy and Legislation</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Legal frameworks supporting conservation:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Nature Conservation Act 2002:</strong> Primary legislation for nature conservation in Tasmania</li>
                    <li><strong>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995:</strong> Provides for protection and management of threatened species</li>
                    <li><strong>Environmental Management and Pollution Control Act 1994:</strong> Addresses pollution and environmental impacts</li>
                    <li><strong>National Parks and Reserves Management Act 2002:</strong> Management of Tasmania's reserve system</li>
                    <li><strong>Forest Practices Act 1985:</strong> Regulates forestry operations to protect environmental values</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="summary-box">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-clipboard-list" aria-hidden="true"></i> Summary: Effective Conservation</h3>
                <p>Successful conservation in Tasmania requires:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>A comprehensive protected area network</li>
                    <li>Targeted species recovery programs</li>
                    <li>Effective threat management</li>
                    <li>Strong policy and legislation</li>
                    <li>Community involvement and support</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="interactive-activity">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-tasks" aria-hidden="true"></i> Activity: Conservation Priority Setting</h3>
                <p>Imagine you are a conservation manager with limited resources. Rank these actions in order of priority for protecting a newly discovered population of a threatened orchid species:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Conduct population survey and mapping</li>
                    <li>Install protective fencing</li>
                    <li>Develop long-term management plan</li>
                    <li>Collect seed for banking</li>
                    <li>Assess threats to the population</li>
                </ol>
                <p>Consider factors like urgency, cost, and potential impact when making your decisions.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Interactive Activities Section -->
