                    <p>Devil Facial Tumor Disease (DFTD), a contagious cancer, has caused population declines of more than 80% since the disease was first observed in 1996.</p>
                    
                    <h4>Response</h4>
                    <p>The Save the Tasmanian Devil Program was established, involving:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Establishing an insurance population in captivity</li>
                        <li>Research into disease transmission and treatment</li>
                        <li>Monitoring wild populations</li>
                        <li>Trialing wild management approaches</li>
                        <li>Community engagement and education</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <h4>Outcomes</h4>
                    <p>While DFTD remains a serious threat, some populations are showing signs of resistance or adaptation. The insurance population has been successful, with over 700 devils in captive breeding facilities across Australia.</p>
