        <!-- Overview Section -->
        <section id="overview" class="content-section active" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="overview-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-info-circle" aria-hidden="true"></i> Legislative Framework Overview</h2>
            <p>Understanding the legislative framework is essential for conducting ecological and cultural site inspections in Tasmania. This module covers the key laws, regulations, compliance requirements, and permit processes that govern site inspections.</p>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-book" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Why Legislation Matters</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Compliance with legislation is not optional—it's a legal requirement. Understanding these laws helps you:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Protect Tasmania's unique natural and cultural heritage</li>
                    <li>Avoid significant penalties for non-compliance</li>
                    <li>Ensure development occurs sustainably</li>
                    <li>Fulfill your duty of care obligations</li>
                    <li>Make informed decisions during site inspections</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Consequences of Non-Compliance</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Failure to comply with relevant legislation can result in:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Substantial fines for individuals and organizations</li>
                    <li>Project delays or cessation of works</li>
                    <li>Legal prosecution</li>
                    <li>Damage to professional reputation</li>
                    <li>Irreversible harm to ecological and cultural values</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-lightbulb" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Key Principles</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Several key principles underpin Tasmania's environmental and heritage legislation:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Precautionary Principle:</strong> Where there are threats of serious or irreversible environmental damage, lack of full scientific certainty should not be used as a reason for postponing measures to prevent environmental degradation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Intergenerational Equity:</strong> Present generations should ensure that the health, diversity, and productivity of the environment is maintained or enhanced for the benefit of future generations.</li>
                    <li><strong>Conservation of Biological Diversity:</strong> Protecting the variety of all life forms - the different plants, animals and microorganisms, the genes they contain, and the ecosystems they form.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <button class="btn" id="next-to-laws"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i> Continue to Key Legislation</button>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Key Legislation Section -->
        <section id="laws" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="laws-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-balance-scale" aria-hidden="true"></i> Key Legislation</h2>
            <p>Tasmania has a comprehensive legislative framework governing ecological and cultural heritage protection. The following table outlines the key acts and regulations:</p>
            
            <table class="law-table">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Legislation</th>
                        <th>Purpose</th>
                        <th>Administering Authority</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Nature Conservation Act 2002</strong></td>
                        <td>Provides for the conservation and protection of Tasmania's flora, fauna, and geological diversity</td>
                        <td>Department of Natural Resources and Environment Tasmania (NRE Tas)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Aboriginal Heritage Act 1975</strong></td>
                        <td>Protects and conserves Aboriginal relics and sites of significance</td>
                        <td>Aboriginal Heritage Tasmania</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Historic Cultural Heritage Act 1995</strong></td>
                        <td>Provides for the protection and conservation of Tasmania's historic cultural heritage</td>
                        <td>Heritage Tasmania</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Environmental Management and Pollution Control Act 1994</strong></td>
                        <td>Provides for the management of pollution and environmental impacts</td>
                        <td>EPA Tasmania</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995</strong></td>
                        <td>Provides for the protection and management of threatened native flora and fauna</td>
                        <td>NRE Tas</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Land Use Planning and Approvals Act 1993</strong></td>
                        <td>Provides for planning schemes and development controls</td>
                        <td>Local Councils & Tasmanian Planning Commission</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-leaf" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Nature Conservation Act 2002</h3>
                </div>
                <p>This is the primary legislation for protecting Tasmania's natural values. Key provisions include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Establishment of reserved land categories (national parks, nature reserves, etc.)</li>
                    <li>Protection of threatened species and communities</li>
                    <li>Regulation of activities that may impact natural values</li>
                    <li>Controls on taking of protected flora and fauna</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Under this Act, certain activities require permits, including scientific research, commercial activities in reserves, and interfering with protected species.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-monument" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Aboriginal Heritage Act 1975</h3>
                </div>
                <p>This Act protects Aboriginal relics and sites of significance. Important aspects include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Automatic protection for all Aboriginal relics, whether registered or not</li>
                    <li>Requirement to report discovery of Aboriginal relics</li>
                    <li>Prohibition of damaging, disturbing, or interfering with Aboriginal relics</li>
                    <li>Provision for the return of Aboriginal ancestral remains</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Any person who discovers a relic must report it to the Minister within 5 days. It is an offense to damage, destroy, or otherwise interfere with a relic without authorization.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-landmark" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Historic Cultural Heritage Act 1995</h3>
                </div>
                <p>This Act provides for the protection of Tasmania's historic heritage. Key elements include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Establishment of the Tasmanian Heritage Register</li>
                    <li>Protection of registered historic heritage places and objects</li>
                    <li>Requirements for works affecting registered places</li>
                    <li>Provision for heritage agreements</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Works that may affect a registered place require a permit from the Heritage Council. This includes demolition, alteration, extension, and subdivision.</p>
            </div>
            
            <button class="btn" id="next-to-compliance"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i> Continue to Compliance Requirements</button>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Compliance Requirements Section -->
        <section id="compliance" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="compliance-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-clipboard-check" aria-hidden="true"></i> Compliance Requirements</h2>
            <p>Understanding your compliance obligations is essential when conducting site inspections. This section outlines key requirements under Tasmanian legislation.</p>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-tree" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Ecological Compliance</h3>
                </div>
                <p>When conducting ecological site inspections, you must comply with:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Threatened Species Surveys:</strong> If potential habitat for threatened species is present, specific surveys may be required at appropriate times of year</li>
                    <li><strong>Vegetation Clearance:</strong> Native vegetation clearance may require permits under various mechanisms</li>
                    <li><strong>Biosecurity Protocols:</strong> Implement measures to prevent the spread of weeds and pathogens</li>
                    <li><strong>Fauna Protection:</strong> Implement measures to protect fauna during works, including pre-clearance surveys and fauna spotting</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-history" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Cultural Heritage Compliance</h3>
                </div>
                <p>When conducting cultural heritage site inspections, you must comply with:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Due Diligence Assessments:</strong> Research and assess potential heritage values before works commence</li>
                    <li><strong>Chance Find Procedures:</strong> Implement protocols for unexpected discoveries of Aboriginal or historic heritage</li>
                    <li><strong>Consultation Requirements:</strong> Engage with relevant Aboriginal communities for Aboriginal heritage assessments</li>
                    <li><strong>Heritage Impact Assessments:</strong> Prepare assessments for works affecting registered heritage places</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-list-check" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Compliance Checklist</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Use this checklist to ensure compliance during site inspections:</p>
                
                <div class="inspection-checklist">
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check1">
                        <label for="check1">Research the Natural Values Atlas for listed species and communities</label>
                    </div>
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check2">
                        <label for="check2">Check the Tasmanian Heritage Register for listed places</label>
                    </div>
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check3">
                        <label for="check3">Consult with Aboriginal Heritage Tasmania for potential Aboriginal heritage values</label>
                    </div>
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check4">
                        <label for="check4">Check local planning scheme provisions and zoning</label>
                    </div>
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check5">
                        <label for="check5">Identify potential impacts on watercourses (Water Management Act 1999)</label>
                    </div>
                    <div class="checklist-item">
                        <input type="checkbox" id="check6">
                        <label for="check6">Assess potential for soil contamination (Environmental Management and Pollution Control Act 1994)</label>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                    <h3>Penalties for Non-Compliance</h3>
                </div>
                <p>Penalties for non-compliance with environmental and heritage legislation can be severe:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Nature Conservation Act:</strong> Up to 2 years imprisonment or $324,000 fine for corporations</li>
                    <li><strong>Aboriginal Heritage Act:</strong> Up to $157,000 fine or 2 years imprisonment for damaging a relic</li>
                    <li><strong>Historic Cultural Heritage Act:</strong> Up to $157,000 fine for damaging a registered place</li>
                    <li><strong>Threatened Species Protection Act:</strong> Up to $324,000 fine for taking a listed species</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Directors and managers may also be held personally liable for offenses committed by their organizations.</p>
            </div>
            
            <button class="btn" id="next-to-permits"><i class="fas fa-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i> Continue to Permit Processes</button>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Permit Processes Section -->
        <section id="permits" class="content-section" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="permits-tab">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-file-contract" aria-hidden="true"></i> Permit Processes</h2>
            <p>Various activities require permits under Tasmanian legislation. Understanding these processes is essential for compliance.</p>
            
